# AppArmor profile: permit the kennel spawn to create unprivileged user namespaces.
#
# Why this exists
# ---------------
# kenneld runs as an ordinary user. To build each workload's sandbox it execs the
# setuid-root privhelper (kennel-privhelper), which establishes an identity-mapped
# *user namespace* — the bubblewrap-equivalent mechanism that grants CAP_SYS_ADMIN
# *inside that namespace* — and constructs the view within it (mount(2), pivot_root).
# Crucially the privhelper clones the userns *as the operator*: it drops its effective
# uid across the clone so the namespace is operator-owned (docs/architecture/01-process-model.md),
# so to the kernel it is an *unprivileged* userns creation despite the setuid bit.
#
# Ubuntu 23.10+/24.04 ship `kernel.apparmor_restrict_unprivileged_userns=1`: under it,
# `clone/unshare(CLONE_NEWUSER)` SUCCEEDS but the creator holds NO capabilities in the
# new namespace (the first /proc/self/setgroups or uid_map/gid_map write is EACCES), so
# the operator-owned spawn cannot proceed. This profile grants the `userns` permission
# to the kenneld binary; the privhelper *inherits it across exec* (see below), restoring
# the capability for the kennel spawn *specifically*, without weakening the host-wide
# restriction for every other binary.
#
# So construction needs BOTH the privhelper's setuid root (mode 4755; file capabilities
# a per-distribution alternative, docs/architecture/07-paths.md) for the map-write and
# mount capabilities, AND this AppArmor grant for the operator-owned userns creation
# under the restriction. Removing the profile breaks construction (the privhelper's
# child cannot write its uid_map: `kennel-bin-init did not report ready`). On hosts that
# do not restrict unprivileged user namespaces, the profile is harmless.
#
# Why flags=(unconfined), not an enforcing profile
# -------------------------------------------------
# This profile's sole job is to GRANT the `userns` capability; it does not confine
# kenneld or the privhelper. The threat model trusts them — the enforcers — and confines
# the *workload*, via Landlock + seccomp + the namespaces + the egress proxy/BPF. An
# enforcing profile cannot work here, for a concrete reason:
#
#   - kenneld execs the privhelper, which (inheriting this profile across exec, since the
#     profile is unconfined and no transition rule names it) must be permitted `userns` +
#     `mount` + `pivot_root` + `capability sys_admin` to build the sandbox;
#   - the privhelper fexecve's kennel-bin-init (PID 1 of the cage), which sets
#     PR_SET_NO_NEW_PRIVS (seccomp requires it) and then execs the *arbitrary* workload;
#   - under no-new-privs the kernel forbids AppArmor from changing the profile at exec —
#     EVERY transition is denied, both `Ux` (to unconfined, a privilege gain) and even
#     `Cx`/`Px` to a *stricter* child profile (verified on 6.17 from the audit log:
#     `apparmor="DENIED" operation="exec" info="no new privs"`).
#
# So an enforcing profile would leave only `ix` (inherit) for the workload exec, which
# would hand the workload kenneld's own `mount`/`userns`/`sys_admin` — strictly worse
# than unconfined. `flags=(unconfined)` (Ubuntu's documented idiom — cf. the stock
# /etc/apparmor.d userns stubs, "exists only to give the application a name") sidesteps
# the transition: the process is already unconfined, so the workload exec needs no
# transition and proceeds, with the workload's confinement left to the kernel mechanisms
# that actually own it. Confining the *workload* via AppArmor would require runtime
# `aa_change_onexec` integration in the spawn (a v2 question, §11.1).
#
# Install
# -------
#   install -m 0644 dist/apparmor/kenneld /etc/apparmor.d/kenneld
#   apparmor_parser -r -W /etc/apparmor.d/kenneld
#
# The attachment path must match the installed kenneld binary
# (docs/architecture/07-paths.md: /usr/libexec/kennel/kenneld). Distributions that
# relocate via KENNEL_LIBEXEC_DIR must adjust the path below to match.

abi <abi/4.0>,
include <tunables/global>

profile kenneld /usr/libexec/kennel/kenneld flags=(unconfined) {
  userns,

  # Site-specific additions and overrides.
  include if exists <local/kenneld>
}
